{"title_page": "Alberto Salazar", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name = Alberto Salazar\n|image = Salazar Eugene 08.JPG\n|imagesize = 225\n|caption = Salazar in 2008\n|fullname = Alberto Sequisha Salazar\n| sport = [[Track and field#Running|Track]], [[Long-distance running]]\n| event = [[5000 metres|5000 meters]], [[10000 metres|10,000 meters]], [[Marathon]]\n| nationality = [[Cuban-Americans|Cuban-American]]\n|alias =\n|club =\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1958|8|7|mf=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Havana]], Cuba<ref name=sports-reference>{{cite web|title=Alberto Salazar|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/sa/alberto-salazar-1.html|website=sports-reference.com|publisher=[[Sports Reference]]|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref>\n|collegeteam = [[Oregon Ducks|Oregon]]\n|height = 5 ft 11 in\n|weight = 141 lb\n|turnedpro =\n|retired in 2009 married to his wife Sequisha Von Gizbergen\n|pb = '''[[5000 metres|5000 meters]]''': 13:11.26<ref name=\"IAAF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/united-states/alberto-salazar-7013|author=IAAF|title=Athlete profile for Alberto Salazar}}</ref> <br> '''[[10000 metres|10,000 meters]]''': 27:25.61<ref name=\"IAAF\"/> <br> '''[[Marathon]]''': 2:08:13<ref name=\"IAAF\"/>\n|olympics =\n|worlds =\n|highestranking =\n|coaching =\n|updated =\n|medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}}\n{{Medal|Sport | Men's [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[1982 IAAF World Cross Country Championships \u2013 Senior men's race|1982 Rome]]|Senior race}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[New York City Marathon]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1982 New York City Marathon|1982 New York]]|Marathon}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1981 New York City Marathon|1981 New York]]|Marathon}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1980 New York City Marathon|1980 New York]]|Marathon}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Boston Marathon]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1982 Boston Marathon|1982 Boston]]|Marathon}}\n}}\n'''Alberto Salazar''' (born August 7, 1958) is an American [[Track and field|track]] coach, former world-class [[long-distance running|long-distance runner]] and a doping offender. Born in [[Cuba]], Salazar immigrated to the United States as a child with his family. They moved to [[Manchester, Connecticut|Manchester]], [[Connecticut]], and then to [[Wayland, Massachusetts|Wayland]], [[Massachusetts]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/salazar_alberto_1958_/#.WDWeZmMrLD4|title=Alberto Salazar (1958 - )|website=oregonencyclopedia.org}}</ref> where Salazar competed in track and field in high school. Salazar is best known for his performances in the [[New York City Marathon]] in the early 1980s and his 1982 [[Boston Marathon]] victory known as the \"Duel in the Sun.\" He held American track records of 13:11.93 for 5,000 m on July 6, 1982 in [[Stockholm]], Sweden and 27:25.61 for 10,000 m on June 26, 1982 in [[Oslo]], Norway.\n\nSalazar was the head coach of the [[Nike Oregon Project]] in [[Portland, Oregon]]. He won the [[IAAF]] Coaching Achievement Award in 2013 during a ceremony hosted by the International Athletics Foundation in [[Monaco]].\n\nIn June 2015, Salazar was named in a joint [[BBC]] ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' and [[ProPublica]] investigation into doping allegations.\n\nIn 2019 Salazar was banned for 4 years from athletics for [[#Doping investigations|doping offenses]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url= https://www.usada.org/sanction/aaa-panel-4-year-sanctions-alberto-salazar-jeffrey-brown/ |title =AAA Panel Imposes 4-Year Sanctions on Alberto Salazar and Dr. Jeffrey Brown for Multiple Anti-Doping Rule Violations |accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> The Nike Oregon Project was shut down in the wake of the controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/news/a29432537/after-salazar-ban-nike-shuts-down-oregon-project/|title=After Salazar Ban, Nike Shuts Down Oregon Project|last=Sgobba|first=Christa|date=2019-10-11|website=Runner's World|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>  \n\nHe was further mired in controversy after the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' published a video [[op-ed]] from his former athlete [[Mary Cain (athlete)|Mary Cain]]. <ref>{{cite news|title=I was the fastest girl in the world until I joined Nike|first=Mary|last=Cain|work=New York Times|date=November 7, 2019|accessdate=November 7, 2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/07/opinion/nike-running-mary-cain.html}}</ref>\n\n==Running career==\n\n===High school===\nBorn in Cuba, Salazar grew up in [[Wayland, Massachusetts]]. His father Jose was a close friend of [[Fidel Castro]] and fellow [[Cuban revolution]]ary, who became an opponent of the Communist government and member of the [[anti-Castro]] movement.{{r|brant200404}} The younger Salazar was an outstanding high school runner who was state cross country champion in 1975. He trained w\u0131th the well known [[Greater Boston Track Club]] (whose members included the likes of [[Bill Rodgers (athlete)|Bill Rodgers]], Randy Thomas, and [[Greg Meyer]]) where he was given the nickname of \"the rookie\".\n\n===Collegiate===\nFrom Massachusetts he went to the [[University of Oregon]] where he won numerous All American honors, was a member of the 1977 NCAA cross country championship team, and won the individual NCAA cross country championship in 1978. Salazar won the 1978 NCAA national cross country championship in cold, snowy conditions, handing Track & Field News Athlete of the Year [[Henry Rono]] one of his few losses of the year. He finished 2nd to Rono in a memorable duel at the 1979 NCAA national cross country championships at [[Lehigh University]], in which Rono (28:19) and Salazar (28:28) ran the 3rd and 5th fastest 10,000 meter cross country times in NCAA championship history. Neither time has been matched in over three decades of NCAA cross country competition since then. After that, he finished third in the Olympic Trials 10,000 meter race in  28:10.42<ref name=\"runnersworld.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/advanced/a20835941/the-1980-u-s-track-field-trials/|title=The 1980 U.S. Track & Field Trials|date=October 1, 1980|website=Runner's World}}</ref> to make the 1980 Olympic team (which didn't compete in the Olympics in Moscow due to the U.S. boycott) and received one of 461 [[List of Congressional Gold Medal recipients|Congressional Gold Medal]]s created especially for the spurned athletes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Caroccioli|first1=Tom|last2=Caroccioli|first2=Jerry|title=Boycott: Stolen Dreams of the 1980 Moscow Olympic Games|publisher=New Chapter Press|location=Highland Park, IL|isbn=978-0942257403|pages=243\u2013253}}</ref> He broke the American indoor 5,000 meter record in February 1981 at the [[Millrose Games]] in New York (his 13:22.6 beating the old AR by nearly 20 seconds as he finished second behind [[Suleiman Nyambui]], who broke the indoor world record with a 13:20.4). Salazar and Bill Rodgers had a legendary duel at the Gurnet Classic Beach Run in Duxbury during the 1970s. At the 1978 [[Falmouth Road Race]] after fading to 10th place, he collapsed at the finish with a temperature of 107 degrees Fahrenheit (41.7&nbsp;\u00b0C) and was read his last rites prematurely.<ref name=\"si_4Sept1978\">{{cite journal|last=Moore|first=Kenny|title=Even In A Crowd He Runs Alone|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=September 4, 1978|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1135819/1/index.htm|accessdate=July 11, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"si_31Oct2007\">{{cite journal|last=Wolff|first=Alexander|title=No Finish Line|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=October 31, 2007|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/web/COM1058763/index.htm|accessdate=July 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Post-collegiate===\nFrom 1980 through 1982, Salazar won three consecutive [[New York City Marathon]]s.{{r|brant200404}} His first-ever marathon, the 1980 New York City race, resulted in a 2:09:41 win, at the time the fastest American debut and the second-fastest time recorded by a U.S. runner (behind Bill Rodgers' 2:09:27 at [[Boston Marathon|Boston]] in 1979). He was on that week's cover of Sports Illustrated after the victory. In 1981, Salazar set an apparent world record at the [[New York City Marathon]] of 2:08:13, surpassing the 12-year-old mark of 2:08:33 set by Australian [[Derek Clayton]] in 1969 in Antwerp, Belgium. However, the course was found on re-measurement to be about 148 meters short of the 42.195 kilometre (26 miles, 385 yards) distance. This is equivalent to about 27 seconds.\n\nIn 1982 he won his first and only [[Boston Marathon]] after the famous \"Duel in the Sun\" with [[Dick Beardsley]].<ref name=sports-reference/> Salazar won the race in an exciting sprint finish and collapsed at the end before being taken to an emergency room and given six liters of saline solution intravenously because he had not drunk during the race.<ref>{{cite book|last=Brant|first=John|title=Duel In The Sun: Alberto Salazar, Dick Beardsley, and America's greatest marathon|publisher=Rodale|year=2006|pages=96|isbn=1-59486-262-1}}</ref> Salazar ended the year ranked #1 in the world in the marathon by [[Track & Field News]] magazine for his wins in Boston and New York, #1 in their North American Road Rankings for his American 10K road record win of 28:04 at the Orange Bowl 10K and his course record of 31:53 at the highly competitive Falmouth {{convert|7.1|mi|km|adj=on}} road race (his second win and course record there), #8 in the world (and #1 American with an AR of 13:11.93) in the 5,000 meters, and #2 in the world in the 10,000 meters, with three second-place finishes at Eugene (27:30.0), at Oslo in an American Record of 27:25.61, and at Paris (27:29.06).\n\nSalazar enjoyed success in cross country competition, earning several All American honors in collegiate and post-collegiate national championships. Salazar was also the U.S. national cross country champion in 1979. He fared well at the [[IAAF World Cross Country Championships]], finishing second in 1982 and fourth in 1983.  His silver medal in 1982 marks the last time an American male reached the podium in World Cross Country.\n\nIn addition to a fourth-place finish (only one second behind the top three placers) at the 1983 world cross country championships, Salazar twice broke the American 10&nbsp;km road record in 1983 with efforts of 28:02 and 28:01 at the Americas 10&nbsp;km and Continental Homes 10&nbsp;km respectively. He finished as the top ranker in Track & Field News magazine's North American Road Rankings for 1983. He was also the 10,000 meter national track champion in 1983, pulling away from [[Craig Virgin]] in the last straightaway at the U.S. championships in Indiana in June to win his second such title (the first coming in 1981). However, he finished last in the 10,000 meters at the World Track & Field Championships while suffering from bronchitis and was beaten for the first time in the marathon, finishing fifth at the Rotterdam marathon in April (2:10:08) and then fifth again at Fukuoka in December (2:09:21). (The latter time would have been the American Record for the next 17 years except that there was a problem in filing the paperwork with the authorities.)\n\nIn 1984, after a 2nd-place finish by Salazar in the 10,000 meters at the [[Mt. SAC Relays]] in 27:45.5, he finished 2nd at the men's Olympic marathon trials (2:11:44) to become a member of the United States' [[Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics - Men's Marathon|Olympic Marathon Team]], along with [[Pete Pfitzinger]] and John Tuttle.  He was considered a favorite to win or medal in the [[1984 Summer Olympics]], but finished a disappointing 15th in 2:14:19 under the hot Los Angeles sun.\n\nSalazar's competitive decline is often attributed to the stress on his body from the famous \"Duel in the Sun\" with Beardsley.{{r|brant200404}} Salazar recounts falling into a \"more-is-better\" mindset which led him to reason that if 120 miles per week yielded a certain level of success, then {{convert|180|mi|km}} or even {{convert|200|mi|km}} would bring even better results. This intense and grueling regimen of such extremely long distances led to a breakdown of his immune system, and he found himself frequently sick, injured, and otherwise unable to continue training. The story of Salazar's 1982 win at the Boston Marathon and his subsequent competitive decline is told in ''[[Duel in the Sun (book)|Duel in the Sun]]'' by John Brant.\n\nAfter failing to make the [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics - Men's Marathon|1988 Olympic Marathon Team]] Salazar opened a successful restaurant in [[Eugene, Oregon]]. Although only able to stagger through four or five miles per run, he remained obsessed with training; Brant wrote that \"He couldn't run, yet he couldn't stop running.\" Salazar unsuccessfully visited the Stanford Sleep Clinic and a cardiologist, had surgery, and trained in Kenya. In 1994 he said that \"For most of the last 10 years, I hated running. I hated it with a passion. I used to wish for a cataclysmic injury in which I would lose one of my legs. I know that sounds terrible, but if I had lost a leg, then I wouldn't have to torture myself anymore.\"{{r|brant200404}}\n\nA doctor diagnosed Salazar's running problems and [[exercise-induced asthma]] as largely due to the 1982 marathon, and successfully prescribed [[Prozac]] to improve his physical symptoms and depression. Salazar closed his restaurant, began training again at the age of 34, and in 1994 won the prestigious {{convert|90|km|mi|abbr=on}} [[Comrades Marathon]]. He soon retired from competing, believing that he had nothing left to prove as a runner, and became a running coach.<ref name=\"brant200404\">{{cite news | url=http://www.runnersworld.com/boston-marathon/duel-in-the-sun | title=Duel in the Sun | work=Runner's World | date=April 2004 | accessdate=April 10, 2015 | author=Brant, John | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916172517/http://www.runnersworld.com/boston-marathon/duel-in-the-sun | archive-date=September 16, 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Salazar stated that Prozac played a role in motivating him to succeed in professional running again; the actual effect of the drug on his performance remains controversial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Salazar's Drug Claim a Concern|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1994-07-03/sports/9407020194_1_prozac-side-effects-endocrine-system|work=Sun Sentinel}}</ref>\n\n==Post-competitive career==\nAfter his competition career, Salazar moved into coaching. By 1996 this included middle distance runner [[Mary Decker]],<ref name=\"decker_salazar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/specials/olympics/cntdown/0501oly-run-slaney.html|title=TRACK AND FIELD; Slaney Tries New Approach to Olympic Quest|last=LONGMAN|first=JERE|date=May 1, 1996|work=New York Times|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref> who at the age of 37 qualified for the [[5000 metres|5000 meters]] at the [[1996 Summer Olympics|Atlanta Olympics]]. However, a [[Urinalysis|urine test]] taken in June at the Olympic Trials showed a [[testosterone (medication)|testosterone]] to [[epitestosterone]] (T/E) ratio greater than the allowable maximum of six to one.<ref name=\"nyt_04_14_99\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/14/sports/track-and-field-slaney-suing-the-iaaf-in-dispute-over-a-drug-test.html|title=TRACK AND FIELD; Slaney Suing the I.A.A.F. In Dispute Over a Drug Test|last=Litsky|first=Frank|date=April 14, 1999|work=New York Times|accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref> While Decker and her lawyers contended that the T/E ratio test is unreliable for women in their late 30s who are taking [[combined oral contraceptive pill|birth control pills]], she was eliminated in the heats at the Olympics.<ref name=\"cnn_si_11_29_1999\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/siforwomen/top_100/31/|title=Mary Decker Slaney, Track and Field |last=MacDonald|first=Jamie|date=November 29, 1999|work=Sports Illustrated for Women|publisher=CNNsi.com|accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref> In June 1997, the IAAF banned Decker from competition. Later reinstated by a USATF panel,<ref name=\"business_week\">{{cite news|url=http://images.businessweek.com/ss/08/08/0808_unretired_athletes/8.htm|title=Athletes Unretiring: The Comeback Kids|work=Business Week|accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"retuers_july_25_2009\">{{cite news|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/sport/archives/2009/07/25/2003449504|title=Runner still feels regret over 1984 Olympics wipeout|date=July 25, 2009|work=Reuters|publisher=Taipei Times|accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref> the IAAF cleared her to compete but took the case to [[arbitration]]. In April 1999, the arbitration panel ruled against her, after which the IAAF through a retroactive ban stripped her of a silver medal she had won in the 1500 meters at the [[1997 IAAF World Indoor Championships|1997 World Indoor Championships]].<ref name=\"ind_4_27_1999\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/athletics-slaney-doping-ban-upheld-at-iaaf-hearing-1089981.html|title= Athletics: Slaney doping ban upheld at IAAF hearing |last=Rowbottom |first=Mike|date=April 27, 1999|work=The Independent|accessdate=December 19, 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nSalazar was employed by [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] as coach of the [[Nike Oregon Project]]. Aimed at producing Olympic-caliber athletes, project members who have trained under Salazar's tutelage include [[Alan Webb (athlete)|Alan Webb]], [[Mo Farah]], [[Galen Rupp]], [[Adam Goucher]], [[Kara Goucher]], [[Dan Browne]], [[Amy Yoder Begley]], [[Sifan Hassan]] and [[Dathan Ritzenhein]]. His connection to Oregon and Oregon Sports gave him the distinction of being inducted into the [[Oregon Sports Hall of Fame]] in 1997. In August 2012 at the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics|London Summer Olympics]], two of Salazar's Olympic-caliber athletes, Mo Farah and Galen Rupp, finished 1st and 2nd respectively in the 10,000&nbsp;m; Farah also went on to win gold in the 5,000&nbsp;m, becoming the first British double Olympian in long distance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/athletics/9454036/Mo-Farahs-American-coach-Alberto-Salazar-on-how-he-helped-runner-step-up-to-win-10000m-gold-at-London-2012.html|title=Mo Farah's American coach Alberto Salazar on how he helped runner 'step up' to win 10,000m gold at London 2012|author=Simon Hart|publisher=  [[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=August 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSalazar ran in the ING New York Marathon in 2006, at age 48, serving as a pacesetter for cyclist [[Lance Armstrong]], who was attempting his first marathon. Salazar was primarily responsible for guiding Armstrong for the first {{convert|10|mi|km}} of the race, while [[Joan Benoit Samuelson]] oversaw the next {{convert|10|mi|km}}, and [[Hicham El Guerrouj]] the final {{convert|6.2|mi|km}}. With their help, Armstrong met his goal of completing the race under three hours, finishing in 2:59:36.\n\nOn Saturday, June 30, 2007, Salazar experienced a serious \"heart event\" and was rushed to the hospital.<ref name=\"si_31Oct2007\" /> On Sunday, July 1 he was reported to be \"groggy\" by his family and remained listed in serious condition.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2007-06-30-3910860095_x.htm 3-time NYC marathon winner Salazar hospitalized with heart problem], [[USA Today]], June 30, 2007.</ref> On July 2, doctors upgraded his condition from \"serious\" to \"fair\". They also confirmed it was a heart attack.<ref>[http://blog.oregonlive.com/sportsupdates/2007/07/salazar_in_fair_condition_afte.html Salazar in fair condition after heart attack], [[The Oregonian]], July 2, 2007</ref> He was released from hospital on July 8.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2007-07-07-3854037618_x.htm Salazar released from hospital one week after heart attack], [[USA Today]], July 8, 2007</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2008, on the eve of the US Olympic trials, Salazar was taken to the hospital again, for dehydration and high blood pressure. He attributes this partially to the stress of coaching five Olympic-hopeful athletes. Afterwards, doctors adjusted his medications, but do not believe that there was any further injury to the heart. He returned to the track to coach his athletes through the trials.<ref>Joel Odom (June 29, 2008). [http://www.oregonlive.com/trackandfield/index.ssf/2008/06/salazar_recovering_after_heart.html Salazar recovering after heart issue], The Oregonian.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Salazar published the autobiography ''14 Minutes: A Running Legend's Life and Death and Life'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.14minutesbook.com/14minutesbook/index |title=14 Minutes: A Running Legend's Life and Death and Life |access-date=January 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123033059/http://www.14minutesbook.com/14minutesbook/index |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> along with John Brant. The book tracks Salazar's story from his family's roots in Cuba, his adolescence in Massachusetts, through his running career to present-day coaching efforts, culminating in his 14-minute-long heart stop in 2007.\n\n===Doping investigations===\nIn June 2015, Salazar was named in a joint [[BBC]] ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' and [[ProPublica]] investigation into doping allegations. This involved testimonies from various athletes and people associated with Salazar about alleged [[microdosing]] of [[Testosterone (medication)|testosterone]] and [[prednisone]] at the [[Nike Oregon Project]]. Salazar declined to be interviewed for the programme, but denied any wrongdoing, saying in a statement that the \"allegations your sources are making are based upon false assumptions and half-truths in an attempt to further their personal agendas\".<ref name=\"BBC Panorama 3 June 2015\">{{cite news |last= Daly |first=Mark |title= Top athletics coach Alberto Salazar faces doping claims|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-32877702 | date=June 3, 2015|website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate=June 3, 2015 }}</ref> One of the more high-profile allegations was made by former Nike Oregon Project athlete [[Kara Goucher]], who claimed she was pressured by Salazar to take thyroid medication not prescribed by her doctor to lose weight gained during her pregnancy in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Kara Goucher Will Remain Publicly Silent on Doping Allegations Against Salazar|url = http://www.runnersworld.com/elite-runners/kara-goucher-will-remain-publicly-silent-on-doping-allegations-against-salazar|website = Runner's World|access-date = February 16, 2016}}</ref> The accusations were addressed by Salazar in public releases.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://nikeoregonproject.com/blogs/news/35522561-alberto-open-letter-part-1 |title= Alberto Open Letter Part 1 |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://nikeoregonproject.com/blogs/news/35523713-alberto-open-letter-part-2 |title= Alberto Open Letter Part 2 |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> \n\nShortly after the allegations, [[Josh Rohatinsky]], who trained under Salazar at the Nike Oregon Project from 2007 until July 2009, used [[Facebook]] to describe both Galen Rupp's relationship with Salazar and the athlete's improved performance as \"highly suspicious\". In the social media posting, Rohatinsky claimed that there had been a \"wall of separation\" between Salazar and Rupp and the rest of the athletes. He also expressed his belief in \"the full extent\" of the witnesses' evidence which appeared in the BBC documentary adding that he also believed that all activity relating to performance-enhancing drugs during his own time at the NOP had been \"limited to Galen Rupp\".<ref name=\"BBC News 14 June 2015\">{{cite web | title= Alberto Salazar: Ex-Oregon Project runner backs BBC's doping claims |url=  https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/33125707| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= June 14, 2015| website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= June 14, 2015}}</ref> \n\nOn October 1, 2019, USADA banned Salazar and Dr. Jeffery Brown, a colleague at the Oregon Project, for doping offences.<ref name=\"auto\"/> These included using a [[World Anti-Doping Agency|WADA]] prohibited method, tampering with doping control methods and trafficking [[Testosterone (medication)|testosterone]] through a prohibited testing program. In response, Salazar stated that \"Throughout this six-year investigation my athletes and I have endured unjust, unethical and highly damaging treatment from USADA. [...] I have always ensured the World Anti-Doping Agency code is strictly followed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/49882757 |title= Alberto Salazar: Mo Farah's former coach banned for four years for doping violations |accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Records of the investigations were unsealed two days later, exposing a pattern of withholding their own medical records from the athletes, ignoring subpoenas, and other forms of delay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2019/10/in-pursuing-salazar-anti-doping-agency-found-itself-fighting-nike.html|title=Pursuing Alberto Salazar, anti-doping agency found itself fighting Nike|last=Manning|first=Jeff|date=2019-10-06|website=oregonlive|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Competition record==\n\n===Marathon===\n{| {{AchievementTable}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"|Representing the {{USA}}\n|-\n|1980\n|[[New York City Marathon]]\n|[[New York City]], [[United States]]\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|2:09:41\n|-\n|1981\n|[[New York City Marathon]]\n|New York, United States\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|2:08:13 <ref>[https://www.arrs.run/MaraRank/ATM_Mara1981.htm World Marathon Rankings for 1981]. arrs.run</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|[[New York City Marathon]]\n|New York, United States\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|2:09:29\n|-\n|[[Boston Marathon]]\n|[[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston, United States]]\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|2:08:52\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983\n|[[Rotterdam Marathon]]\n|[[Rotterdam, Netherlands]]\n|5th\n|2:10:08\n|-\n|[[Fukuoka Marathon]]\n|[[Fukuoka, Japan]]\n|5th\n|2:09:21\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1984\n|[[United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic Trials]]\n|[[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], United States\n|bgcolor=\"Silver\" | 2nd\n|2:11:44<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://subscribe.hearstmags.com/circulation/shared/index.html|title=Hearst Magazines|website=subscribe.hearstmags.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[1984 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|[[Los Angeles, California]]\n|15th\n|2:14:19\n|}\n\n===Track and Field===\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Representing the {{USA}}\n|-\n|1980\n|[[United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic Trials]]\n|[[Walnut, California|Walnut]], [[California]]\n|bgcolor=cc9900 | 3rd\n|10,000 m\n| 28:10.42<ref name=\"runnersworld.com\"/>\n|-\n|1981\n|[[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]]\n|[[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]]\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\" | 1st \n|10,000 m\n|28:39.33<ref name=\"usanc\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/index.php/tafn-presults?list_id=36&sex_id=M&event_id=12 |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 25, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425224911/http://trackandfieldnews.com/index.php/tafn-presults?list_id=36&sex_id=M&event_id=12 |archive-date=April 25, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|1983\n|[[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]]\n| [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]]\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\" | 1st\n|10,000 m\n|28:11.64<ref name=\"usanc\"/>\n|}\n\n===Cross country===\n{| {{AchievementTable}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"|Representing the {{USA}}\n|-\n|1979\n|[[USA Cross Country Championships]]\n|{{sortdash}}\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|{{sortdash}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|USA Cross Country Trials\n|[[Pocatello, Idaho]]\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|36:52.4\n|-\n|[[IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|33:44.8\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983\n|USA Cross Country Trials\n|[[Edwardsville, Illinois]]\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|36:34\n|-\n|[[1983 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Gateshead, England]]\n|bgcolor= |4th\n|36:53\n|}\n\n===NCAA cross country===\n{|{{AchievementTable}}\n!colspan=5| Representing [[Oregon Ducks track and field|Oregon]]\n|-\n|1977\n||[[NCAA Men's Division I Cross Country Championship|NCAA Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Pullman, Washington]]\n|9th\n|29:20.8\n|-\n|1978\n|[[NCAA Men's Division I Cross Country Championship|NCAA Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]], [[Wisconsin]]\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|29:29.7<ref>https://www.legacy.usatf.org/events/2011/USAXCChampionships/mediaGuide.pdf</ref>\n|-\n|1979\n|[[NCAA Men's Division I Cross Country Championship|NCAA Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|28:37.4\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Cuban Americans|List of Famous Cuban-Americans]]\n*[[List of winners of the Boston Marathon]]\n*[[List of winners of the New York City Marathon]]\n*List of winners of the [[NCAA Men's Cross Country Championship]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Kahn |first=Jennifer |authorlink= |date=November 8, 2010 |title=The Sporting Scene: The Perfect Stride |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |volume=86 |issue=35 |pages=34\u201339 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2010/11/08/101108fa_fact_kahn |accessdate=November 25, 2011}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.brunningmag.cz/blog/we-named-our-dog-after-zatopek Interview with Alberto Salazar about Galen Rupp 2018 (B magazine)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110318150411/http://www.flotrack.org/coverage/238557-The-Pros-in-2011/video/353077-Get-to-Know-Alberto-Salazar Interview with Alberto Salazar (flotrack)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110710081017/http://competitorradio.competitor.com/2011/03/alberto-salazar/ Podcast with Alberto Salazar (competitor radio)]\n<br>\n{{2000 National Distance Running Hall of Fame inductees}}\n{{Footer WBYP Marathon Men}}\n{{Footer New York Marathon Champions Men}}\n{{Footer Boston Marathon Champions Men}}\n{{Footer USA Track & Field 1984 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer US NC 10000m Men}}\n{{Footer Nike Oregon Project}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salazar, Alberto}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male long-distance runners]]\n[[Category:American male marathon runners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Olympic track and field athletes of the United States]]\n[[Category:Oregon Ducks men's track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Cuban emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:People from Wayland, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American track and field coaches]]\n[[Category:New York City Marathon male winners]]\n[[Category:Boston Marathon male winners]]\n[[Category:Congressional Gold Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:Sports coaches from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Oregon Ducks men's cross country runners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name = Alberto Salazar\n|image = Salazar Eugene 08.JPG\n|imagesize = 225\n|caption = Salazar in 2008\n|fullname = Alberto Sequisha Salazar\n| sport = [[Track and field#Running|Track]], [[Long-distance running]]\n| event = [[5000 metres|5000 meters]], [[10000 metres|10,000 meters]], [[Marathon]]\n| nationality = [[Cuban-Americans|Cuban-American]]\n|alias =\n|club =\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1958|8|7|mf=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Havana]], Cuba<ref name=sports-reference>{{cite web|title=Alberto Salazar|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/sa/alberto-salazar-1.html|website=sports-reference.com|publisher=[[Sports Reference]]|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref>\n|collegeteam = [[Oregon Ducks|Oregon]]\n|height = 5 ft 11 in\n|weight = 141 lb\n|turnedpro =\n|retired in 2009 married to his wife Sequisha Von Gizbergen\n|pb = '''[[5000 metres|5000 meters]]''': 13:11.26<ref name=\"IAAF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/united-states/alberto-salazar-7013|author=IAAF|title=Athlete profile for Alberto Salazar}}</ref> <br> '''[[10000 metres|10,000 meters]]''': 27:25.61<ref name=\"IAAF\"/> <br> '''[[Marathon]]''': 2:08:13<ref name=\"IAAF\"/>\n|olympics =\n|worlds =\n|highestranking =\n|coaching =\n|updated =\n|medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}}\n{{Medal|Sport | Men's [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[1982 IAAF World Cross Country Championships \u2013 Senior men's race|1982 Rome]]|Senior race}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[New York City Marathon]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1982 New York City Marathon|1982 New York]]|Marathon}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1981 New York City Marathon|1981 New York]]|Marathon}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1980 New York City Marathon|1980 New York]]|Marathon}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Boston Marathon]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1982 Boston Marathon|1982 Boston]]|Marathon}}\n}}\n'''Alberto Salazar''' (born August 7, 1958) is an American [[Track and field|track]] coach, former world-class [[long-distance running|long-distance runner]] and a doping offender. Born in [[Cuba]], Salazar immigrated to the United States as a child with his family. They moved to [[Manchester, Connecticut|Manchester]], [[Connecticut]] and then to [[Wayland, Massachusetts|Wayland]], [[Massachusetts]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/salazar_alberto_1958_/#.WDWeZmMrLD4|title=Alberto Salazar (1958 - )|website=oregonencyclopedia.org}}</ref> where Salazar competed in track and field in high school. Salazar is best known for his performances in the [[New York City Marathon]] in the early 1980s and his 1982 [[Boston Marathon]] victory known as the \"Duel in the Sun.\" He held American track records of 13:11.93 for 5,000 m on July 6, 1982 in [[Stockholm]], Sweden and 27:25.61 for 10,000 m on June 26, 1982 in [[Oslo]], Norway.\n\nSalazar was the head coach of the [[Nike Oregon Project]] in [[Portland, Oregon]]. He won the [[IAAF]] Coaching Achievement Award in 2013 during a ceremony hosted by the International Athletics Foundation in [[Monaco]].\n\nIn June 2015, Salazar was named in a joint [[BBC]] ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' and [[ProPublica]] investigation into doping allegations.\n\nIn 2019 Salazar was banned for 4 years from athletics for [[#Doping investigations|doping offenses]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url= https://www.usada.org/sanction/aaa-panel-4-year-sanctions-alberto-salazar-jeffrey-brown/ |title =AAA Panel Imposes 4-Year Sanctions on Alberto Salazar and Dr. Jeffrey Brown for Multiple Anti-Doping Rule Violations |accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> The Nike Oregon Project was shut down in the wake of the controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/news/a29432537/after-salazar-ban-nike-shuts-down-oregon-project/|title=After Salazar Ban, Nike Shuts Down Oregon Project|last=Sgobba|first=Christa|date=2019-10-11|website=Runner's World|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>  \n\nHe was further mired in controversy after the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' published a video [[op-ed]] from his former athlete [[Mary Cain (athlete)|Mary Cain]]. <ref>{{cite news|title=I was the fastest girl in the world until I joined Nike|first=Mary|last=Cain|work=New York Times|date=November 7, 2019|accessdate=November 7, 2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/07/opinion/nike-running-mary-cain.html}}</ref>\n\n==Running career==\n\n===High school===\nBorn in Cuba, Salazar grew up in [[Wayland, Massachusetts]]. His father Jose was a close friend of [[Fidel Castro]] and fellow [[Cuban revolution]]ary, who became an opponent of the Communist government and member of the [[anti-Castro]] movement.{{r|brant200404}} The younger Salazar was an outstanding high school runner who was state cross country champion in 1975. He trained w\u0131th the well known [[Greater Boston Track Club]] (whose members included the likes of [[Bill Rodgers (athlete)|Bill Rodgers]], Randy Thomas, and [[Greg Meyer]]) where he was given the nickname of \"the rookie\".\n\n===Collegiate===\nFrom Massachusetts he went to the [[University of Oregon]] where he won numerous All American honors, was a member of the 1977 NCAA cross country championship team, and won the individual NCAA cross country championship in 1978. Salazar won the 1978 NCAA national cross country championship in cold, snowy conditions, handing Track & Field News Athlete of the Year [[Henry Rono]] one of his few losses of the year. He finished 2nd to Rono in a memorable duel at the 1979 NCAA national cross country championships at [[Lehigh University]], in which Rono (28:19) and Salazar (28:28) ran the 3rd and 5th fastest 10,000 meter cross country times in NCAA championship history. Neither time has been matched in over three decades of NCAA cross country competition since then. After that, he finished third in the Olympic Trials 10,000 meter race in  28:10.42<ref name=\"runnersworld.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/advanced/a20835941/the-1980-u-s-track-field-trials/|title=The 1980 U.S. Track & Field Trials|date=October 1, 1980|website=Runner's World}}</ref> to make the 1980 Olympic team (which didn't compete in the Olympics in Moscow due to the U.S. boycott) and received one of 461 [[List of Congressional Gold Medal recipients|Congressional Gold Medal]]s created especially for the spurned athletes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Caroccioli|first1=Tom|last2=Caroccioli|first2=Jerry|title=Boycott: Stolen Dreams of the 1980 Moscow Olympic Games|publisher=New Chapter Press|location=Highland Park, IL|isbn=978-0942257403|pages=243\u2013253}}</ref> He broke the American indoor 5,000 meter record in February 1981 at the [[Millrose Games]] in New York (his 13:22.6 beating the old AR by nearly 20 seconds as he finished second behind [[Suleiman Nyambui]], who broke the indoor world record with a 13:20.4). Salazar and Bill Rodgers had a legendary duel at the Gurnet Classic Beach Run in Duxbury during the 1970s. At the 1978 [[Falmouth Road Race]] after fading to 10th place, he collapsed at the finish with a temperature of 107 degrees Fahrenheit (41.7&nbsp;\u00b0C) and was read his last rites prematurely.<ref name=\"si_4Sept1978\">{{cite journal|last=Moore|first=Kenny|title=Even In A Crowd He Runs Alone|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=September 4, 1978|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1135819/1/index.htm|accessdate=July 11, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"si_31Oct2007\">{{cite journal|last=Wolff|first=Alexander|title=No Finish Line|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=October 31, 2007|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/web/COM1058763/index.htm|accessdate=July 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Post-collegiate===\nFrom 1980 through 1982, Salazar won three consecutive [[New York City Marathon]]s.{{r|brant200404}} His first-ever marathon, the 1980 New York City race, resulted in a 2:09:41 win, at the time the fastest American debut and the second-fastest time recorded by a U.S. runner (behind Bill Rodgers' 2:09:27 at [[Boston Marathon|Boston]] in 1979). He was on that week's cover of Sports Illustrated after the victory. In 1981, Salazar set an apparent world record at the [[New York City Marathon]] of 2:08:13, surpassing the 12-year-old mark of 2:08:33 set by Australian [[Derek Clayton]] in 1969 in Antwerp, Belgium. However, the course was found on re-measurement to be about 148 meters short of the 42.195 kilometre (26 miles, 385 yards) distance. This is equivalent to about 27 seconds.\n\nIn 1982 he won his first and only [[Boston Marathon]] after the famous \"Duel in the Sun\" with [[Dick Beardsley]].<ref name=sports-reference/> Salazar won the race in an exciting sprint finish and collapsed at the end before being taken to an emergency room and given six liters of saline solution intravenously because he had not drunk during the race.<ref>{{cite book|last=Brant|first=John|title=Duel In The Sun: Alberto Salazar, Dick Beardsley, and America's greatest marathon|publisher=Rodale|year=2006|pages=96|isbn=1-59486-262-1}}</ref> Salazar ended the year ranked #1 in the world in the marathon by [[Track & Field News]] magazine for his wins in Boston and New York, #1 in their North American Road Rankings for his American 10K road record win of 28:04 at the Orange Bowl 10K and his course record of 31:53 at the highly competitive Falmouth {{convert|7.1|mi|km|adj=on}} road race (his second win and course record there), #8 in the world (and #1 American with an AR of 13:11.93) in the 5,000 meters, and #2 in the world in the 10,000 meters, with three second-place finishes at Eugene (27:30.0), at Oslo in an American Record of 27:25.61, and at Paris (27:29.06).\n\nSalazar enjoyed success in cross country competition, earning several All American honors in collegiate and post-collegiate national championships. Salazar was also the U.S. national cross country champion in 1979. He fared well at the [[IAAF World Cross Country Championships]], finishing second in 1982 and fourth in 1983.  His silver medal in 1982 marks the last time an American male reached the podium in World Cross Country.\n\nIn addition to a fourth-place finish (only one second behind the top three placers) at the 1983 world cross country championships, Salazar twice broke the American 10&nbsp;km road record in 1983 with efforts of 28:02 and 28:01 at the Americas 10&nbsp;km and Continental Homes 10&nbsp;km respectively. He finished as the top ranker in Track & Field News magazine's North American Road Rankings for 1983. He was also the 10,000 meter national track champion in 1983, pulling away from [[Craig Virgin]] in the last straightaway at the U.S. championships in Indiana in June to win his second such title (the first coming in 1981). However, he finished last in the 10,000 meters at the World Track & Field Championships while suffering from bronchitis and was beaten for the first time in the marathon, finishing fifth at the Rotterdam marathon in April (2:10:08) and then fifth again at Fukuoka in December (2:09:21). (The latter time would have been the American Record for the next 17 years except that there was a problem in filing the paperwork with the authorities.)\n\nIn 1984, after a 2nd-place finish by Salazar in the 10,000 meters at the [[Mt. SAC Relays]] in 27:45.5, he finished 2nd at the men's Olympic marathon trials (2:11:44) to become a member of the United States' [[Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics - Men's Marathon|Olympic Marathon Team]], along with [[Pete Pfitzinger]] and John Tuttle.  He was considered a favorite to win or medal in the [[1984 Summer Olympics]], but finished a disappointing 15th in 2:14:19 under the hot Los Angeles sun.\n\nSalazar's competitive decline is often attributed to the stress on his body from the famous \"Duel in the Sun\" with Beardsley.{{r|brant200404}} Salazar recounts falling into a \"more-is-better\" mindset which led him to reason that if 120 miles per week yielded a certain level of success, then {{convert|180|mi|km}} or even {{convert|200|mi|km}} would bring even better results. This intense and grueling regimen of such extremely long distances led to a breakdown of his immune system, and he found himself frequently sick, injured, and otherwise unable to continue training. The story of Salazar's 1982 win at the Boston Marathon and his subsequent competitive decline is told in ''[[Duel in the Sun (book)|Duel in the Sun]]'' by John Brant.\n\nAfter failing to make the [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics - Men's Marathon|1988 Olympic Marathon Team]] Salazar opened a successful restaurant in [[Eugene, Oregon]]. Although only able to stagger through four or five miles per run, he remained obsessed with training; Brant wrote that \"He couldn't run, yet he couldn't stop running.\" Salazar unsuccessfully visited the Stanford Sleep Clinic and a cardiologist, had surgery, and trained in Kenya. In 1994 he said that \"For most of the last 10 years, I hated running. I hated it with a passion. I used to wish for a cataclysmic injury in which I would lose one of my legs. I know that sounds terrible, but if I had lost a leg, then I wouldn't have to torture myself anymore.\"{{r|brant200404}}\n\nA doctor diagnosed Salazar's running problems and [[exercise-induced asthma]] as largely due to the 1982 marathon, and successfully prescribed [[Prozac]] to improve his physical symptoms and depression. Salazar closed his restaurant, began training again at the age of 34, and in 1994 won the prestigious {{convert|90|km|mi|abbr=on}} [[Comrades Marathon]]. He soon retired from competing, believing that he had nothing left to prove as a runner, and became a running coach.<ref name=\"brant200404\">{{cite news | url=http://www.runnersworld.com/boston-marathon/duel-in-the-sun | title=Duel in the Sun | work=Runner's World | date=April 2004 | accessdate=April 10, 2015 | author=Brant, John | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916172517/http://www.runnersworld.com/boston-marathon/duel-in-the-sun | archive-date=September 16, 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Salazar stated that Prozac played a role in motivating him to succeed in professional running again; the actual effect of the drug on his performance remains controversial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Salazar's Drug Claim a Concern|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1994-07-03/sports/9407020194_1_prozac-side-effects-endocrine-system|work=Sun Sentinel}}</ref>\n\n==Post-competitive career==\nAfter his competition career, Salazar moved into coaching. By 1996 this included middle distance runner [[Mary Decker]],<ref name=\"decker_salazar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/specials/olympics/cntdown/0501oly-run-slaney.html|title=TRACK AND FIELD; Slaney Tries New Approach to Olympic Quest|last=LONGMAN|first=JERE|date=May 1, 1996|work=New York Times|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref> who at the age of 37 qualified for the [[5000 metres|5000 meters]] at the [[1996 Summer Olympics|Atlanta Olympics]]. However, a [[Urinalysis|urine test]] taken in June at the Olympic Trials showed a [[testosterone (medication)|testosterone]] to [[epitestosterone]] (T/E) ratio greater than the allowable maximum of six to one.<ref name=\"nyt_04_14_99\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/14/sports/track-and-field-slaney-suing-the-iaaf-in-dispute-over-a-drug-test.html|title=TRACK AND FIELD; Slaney Suing the I.A.A.F. In Dispute Over a Drug Test|last=Litsky|first=Frank|date=April 14, 1999|work=New York Times|accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref> While Decker and her lawyers contended that the T/E ratio test is unreliable for women in their late 30s who are taking [[combined oral contraceptive pill|birth control pills]], she was eliminated in the heats at the Olympics.<ref name=\"cnn_si_11_29_1999\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/siforwomen/top_100/31/|title=Mary Decker Slaney, Track and Field |last=MacDonald|first=Jamie|date=November 29, 1999|work=Sports Illustrated for Women|publisher=CNNsi.com|accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref> In June 1997, the IAAF banned Decker from competition. Later reinstated by a USATF panel,<ref name=\"business_week\">{{cite news|url=http://images.businessweek.com/ss/08/08/0808_unretired_athletes/8.htm|title=Athletes Unretiring: The Comeback Kids|work=Business Week|accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"retuers_july_25_2009\">{{cite news|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/sport/archives/2009/07/25/2003449504|title=Runner still feels regret over 1984 Olympics wipeout|date=July 25, 2009|work=Reuters|publisher=Taipei Times|accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref> the IAAF cleared her to compete but took the case to [[arbitration]]. In April 1999, the arbitration panel ruled against her, after which the IAAF through a retroactive ban stripped her of a silver medal she had won in the 1500 meters at the [[1997 IAAF World Indoor Championships|1997 World Indoor Championships]].<ref name=\"ind_4_27_1999\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/athletics-slaney-doping-ban-upheld-at-iaaf-hearing-1089981.html|title= Athletics: Slaney doping ban upheld at IAAF hearing |last=Rowbottom |first=Mike|date=April 27, 1999|work=The Independent|accessdate=December 19, 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nSalazar was employed by [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] as coach of the [[Nike Oregon Project]]. Aimed at producing Olympic-caliber athletes, project members who have trained under Salazar's tutelage include [[Alan Webb (athlete)|Alan Webb]], [[Mo Farah]], [[Galen Rupp]], [[Adam Goucher]], [[Kara Goucher]], [[Dan Browne]], [[Amy Yoder Begley]], [[Sifan Hassan]] and [[Dathan Ritzenhein]]. His connection to Oregon and Oregon Sports gave him the distinction of being inducted into the [[Oregon Sports Hall of Fame]] in 1997. In August 2012 at the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics|London Summer Olympics]], two of Salazar's Olympic-caliber athletes, Mo Farah and Galen Rupp, finished 1st and 2nd respectively in the 10,000&nbsp;m; Farah also went on to win gold in the 5,000&nbsp;m, becoming the first British double Olympian in long distance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/athletics/9454036/Mo-Farahs-American-coach-Alberto-Salazar-on-how-he-helped-runner-step-up-to-win-10000m-gold-at-London-2012.html|title=Mo Farah's American coach Alberto Salazar on how he helped runner 'step up' to win 10,000m gold at London 2012|author=Simon Hart|publisher=  [[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=August 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSalazar ran in the ING New York Marathon in 2006, at age 48, serving as a pacesetter for cyclist [[Lance Armstrong]], who was attempting his first marathon. Salazar was primarily responsible for guiding Armstrong for the first {{convert|10|mi|km}} of the race, while [[Joan Benoit Samuelson]] oversaw the next {{convert|10|mi|km}}, and [[Hicham El Guerrouj]] the final {{convert|6.2|mi|km}}. With their help, Armstrong met his goal of completing the race under three hours, finishing in 2:59:36.\n\nOn Saturday, June 30, 2007, Salazar experienced a serious \"heart event\" and was rushed to the hospital.<ref name=\"si_31Oct2007\" /> On Sunday, July 1 he was reported to be \"groggy\" by his family and remained listed in serious condition.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2007-06-30-3910860095_x.htm 3-time NYC marathon winner Salazar hospitalized with heart problem], [[USA Today]], June 30, 2007.</ref> On July 2, doctors upgraded his condition from \"serious\" to \"fair\". They also confirmed it was a heart attack.<ref>[http://blog.oregonlive.com/sportsupdates/2007/07/salazar_in_fair_condition_afte.html Salazar in fair condition after heart attack], [[The Oregonian]], July 2, 2007</ref> He was released from hospital on July 8.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/2007-07-07-3854037618_x.htm Salazar released from hospital one week after heart attack], [[USA Today]], July 8, 2007</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2008, on the eve of the US Olympic trials, Salazar was taken to the hospital again, for dehydration and high blood pressure. He attributes this partially to the stress of coaching five Olympic-hopeful athletes. Afterwards, doctors adjusted his medications, but do not believe that there was any further injury to the heart. He returned to the track to coach his athletes through the trials.<ref>Joel Odom (June 29, 2008). [http://www.oregonlive.com/trackandfield/index.ssf/2008/06/salazar_recovering_after_heart.html Salazar recovering after heart issue], The Oregonian.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Salazar published the autobiography ''14 Minutes: A Running Legend's Life and Death and Life'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.14minutesbook.com/14minutesbook/index |title=14 Minutes: A Running Legend's Life and Death and Life |access-date=January 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123033059/http://www.14minutesbook.com/14minutesbook/index |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> along with John Brant. The book tracks Salazar's story from his family's roots in Cuba, his adolescence in Massachusetts, through his running career to present-day coaching efforts, culminating in his 14-minute-long heart stop in 2007.\n\n===Doping investigations===\nIn June 2015, Salazar was named in a joint [[BBC]] ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' and [[ProPublica]] investigation into doping allegations. This involved testimonies from various athletes and people associated with Salazar about alleged [[microdosing]] of [[Testosterone (medication)|testosterone]] and [[prednisone]] at the [[Nike Oregon Project]]. Salazar declined to be interviewed for the programme, but denied any wrongdoing, saying in a statement that the \"allegations your sources are making are based upon false assumptions and half-truths in an attempt to further their personal agendas\".<ref name=\"BBC Panorama 3 June 2015\">{{cite news |last= Daly |first=Mark |title= Top athletics coach Alberto Salazar faces doping claims|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-32877702 | date=June 3, 2015|website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate=June 3, 2015 }}</ref> One of the more high-profile allegations was made by former Nike Oregon Project athlete [[Kara Goucher]], who claimed she was pressured by Salazar to take thyroid medication not prescribed by her doctor to lose weight gained during her pregnancy in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Kara Goucher Will Remain Publicly Silent on Doping Allegations Against Salazar|url = http://www.runnersworld.com/elite-runners/kara-goucher-will-remain-publicly-silent-on-doping-allegations-against-salazar|website = Runner's World|access-date = February 16, 2016}}</ref> The accusations were addressed by Salazar in public releases.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://nikeoregonproject.com/blogs/news/35522561-alberto-open-letter-part-1 |title= Alberto Open Letter Part 1 |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://nikeoregonproject.com/blogs/news/35523713-alberto-open-letter-part-2 |title= Alberto Open Letter Part 2 |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> \n\nShortly after the allegations, [[Josh Rohatinsky]], who trained under Salazar at the Nike Oregon Project from 2007 until July 2009, used [[Facebook]] to describe both Galen Rupp's relationship with Salazar and the athlete's improved performance as \"highly suspicious\". In the social media posting, Rohatinsky claimed that there had been a \"wall of separation\" between Salazar and Rupp and the rest of the athletes. He also expressed his belief in \"the full extent\" of the witnesses' evidence which appeared in the BBC documentary adding that he also believed that all activity relating to performance-enhancing drugs during his own time at the NOP had been \"limited to Galen Rupp\".<ref name=\"BBC News 14 June 2015\">{{cite web | title= Alberto Salazar: Ex-Oregon Project runner backs BBC's doping claims |url=  https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/33125707| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= June 14, 2015| website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= June 14, 2015}}</ref> \n\nOn October 1, 2019, USADA banned Salazar and Dr. Jeffery Brown, a colleague at the Oregon Project, for doping offences.<ref name=\"auto\"/> These included using a [[World Anti-Doping Agency|WADA]] prohibited method, tampering with doping control methods and trafficking [[Testosterone (medication)|testosterone]] through a prohibited testing program. In response, Salazar stated that \"Throughout this six-year investigation my athletes and I have endured unjust, unethical and highly damaging treatment from USADA. [...] I have always ensured the World Anti-Doping Agency code is strictly followed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/49882757 |title= Alberto Salazar: Mo Farah's former coach banned for four years for doping violations |accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Records of the investigations were unsealed two days later, exposing a pattern of withholding their own medical records from the athletes, ignoring subpoenas, and other forms of delay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2019/10/in-pursuing-salazar-anti-doping-agency-found-itself-fighting-nike.html|title=Pursuing Alberto Salazar, anti-doping agency found itself fighting Nike|last=Manning|first=Jeff|date=2019-10-06|website=oregonlive|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Competition record==\n\n===Marathon===\n{| {{AchievementTable}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"|Representing the {{USA}}\n|-\n|1980\n|[[New York City Marathon]]\n|[[New York City]], [[United States]]\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|2:09:41\n|-\n|1981\n|[[New York City Marathon]]\n|New York, United States\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|2:08:13 <ref>[https://www.arrs.run/MaraRank/ATM_Mara1981.htm World Marathon Rankings for 1981]. arrs.run</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|[[New York City Marathon]]\n|New York, United States\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|2:09:29\n|-\n|[[Boston Marathon]]\n|[[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston, United States]]\n|bgcolor=\"gold\" | 1st\n|2:08:52\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983\n|[[Rotterdam Marathon]]\n|[[Rotterdam, Netherlands]]\n|5th\n|2:10:08\n|-\n|[[Fukuoka Marathon]]\n|[[Fukuoka, Japan]]\n|5th\n|2:09:21\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1984\n|[[United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic Trials]]\n|[[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], United States\n|bgcolor=\"Silver\" | 2nd\n|2:11:44<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://subscribe.hearstmags.com/circulation/shared/index.html|title=Hearst Magazines|website=subscribe.hearstmags.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[1984 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|[[Los Angeles, California]]\n|15th\n|2:14:19\n|}\n\n===Track and Field===\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Representing the {{USA}}\n|-\n|1980\n|[[United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic Trials]]\n|[[Walnut, California|Walnut]], [[California]]\n|bgcolor=cc9900 | 3rd\n|10,000 m\n| 28:10.42<ref name=\"runnersworld.com\"/>\n|-\n|1981\n|[[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]]\n|[[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]]\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\" | 1st \n|10,000 m\n|28:39.33<ref name=\"usanc\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/index.php/tafn-presults?list_id=36&sex_id=M&event_id=12 |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 25, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425224911/http://trackandfieldnews.com/index.php/tafn-presults?list_id=36&sex_id=M&event_id=12 |archive-date=April 25, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|1983\n|[[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]]\n| [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]]\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\" | 1st\n|10,000 m\n|28:11.64<ref name=\"usanc\"/>\n|}\n\n===Cross country===\n{| {{AchievementTable}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"|Representing the {{USA}}\n|-\n|1979\n|[[USA Cross Country Championships]]\n|{{sortdash}}\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|{{sortdash}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|USA Cross Country Trials\n|[[Pocatello, Idaho]]\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|36:52.4\n|-\n|[[IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|33:44.8\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983\n|USA Cross Country Trials\n|[[Edwardsville, Illinois]]\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|36:34\n|-\n|[[1983 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Gateshead, England]]\n|bgcolor= |4th\n|36:53\n|}\n\n===NCAA cross country===\n{|{{AchievementTable}}\n!colspan=5| Representing [[Oregon Ducks track and field|Oregon]]\n|-\n|1977\n||[[NCAA Men's Division I Cross Country Championship|NCAA Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Pullman, Washington]]\n|9th\n|29:20.8\n|-\n|1978\n|[[NCAA Men's Division I Cross Country Championship|NCAA Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]], [[Wisconsin]]\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|29:29.7<ref>https://www.legacy.usatf.org/events/2011/USAXCChampionships/mediaGuide.pdf</ref>\n|-\n|1979\n|[[NCAA Men's Division I Cross Country Championship|NCAA Cross Country Championships]]\n|[[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|28:37.4\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Cuban Americans|List of Famous Cuban-Americans]]\n*[[List of winners of the Boston Marathon]]\n*[[List of winners of the New York City Marathon]]\n*List of winners of the [[NCAA Men's Cross Country Championship]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Kahn |first=Jennifer |authorlink= |date=November 8, 2010 |title=The Sporting Scene: The Perfect Stride |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |volume=86 |issue=35 |pages=34\u201339 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2010/11/08/101108fa_fact_kahn |accessdate=November 25, 2011}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.brunningmag.cz/blog/we-named-our-dog-after-zatopek Interview with Alberto Salazar about Galen Rupp 2018 (B magazine)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110318150411/http://www.flotrack.org/coverage/238557-The-Pros-in-2011/video/353077-Get-to-Know-Alberto-Salazar Interview with Alberto Salazar (flotrack)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110710081017/http://competitorradio.competitor.com/2011/03/alberto-salazar/ Podcast with Alberto Salazar (competitor radio)]\n<br>\n{{2000 National Distance Running Hall of Fame inductees}}\n{{Footer WBYP Marathon Men}}\n{{Footer New York Marathon Champions Men}}\n{{Footer Boston Marathon Champions Men}}\n{{Footer USA Track & Field 1984 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer US NC 10000m Men}}\n{{Footer Nike Oregon Project}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salazar, Alberto}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male long-distance runners]]\n[[Category:American male marathon runners]